<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-04-25T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-04-25T17:00:00-05:00" n="772" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d772">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.01 Manchuria/151: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Minister in Switzerland (<persName corresp="#p_WHR1" type="to">Wilson</persName>)</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-04-25T18:00:00-04:00">April 25, 1932—6
                                p.m.</date></dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>57. For the Secretary of State. In reply to special inquiry by Department
                            regarding items reported concerning <persName corresp="#p_OC1">Ohashi</persName>, until recently Japanese Consul General at
                            Harbin, Legation, Peiping, telegraphs under date April 25: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“<persName corresp="#p_OC1">Ohashi</persName> will be in charge
                                    of general affairs in the Foreign Office at Changchun. In this
                                    capacity the foreign affairs of the new government will
                                    practically be in his hands.”</p></quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><persName corresp="#p_CWR1"><hi rend="smallcaps">Castle</hi></persName></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>